{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2274f9bf-d663-4bf2-8aa8-ce9f2209f969","content":"There's no repo here, so here's general guidance for migrating from `VSTest@3` to **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** in Azure DevOps.\n\n### 1. Update your test projects\n\nAdd the MSTest runner and enable the new platform:\n\n```xml\n<!-- In each test .csproj -->\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <!-- TRX + code-coverage extensions -->\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<ItemGroup>\n  <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n  <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n### 2. Replace `VSTest@3` in your pipeline\n\nThe new platform produces standalone executables. Use `dotnet test` (or run the test exe directly) with the `--` separator for platform options:\n\n```yaml\n# Before (VSTest@3)\n- task: VSTest@3\n  inputs:\n    testAssemblyVer2: '**/*.Tests.dll'\n    resultsFolder: $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n    codeCoverageEnabled: true\n\n# After (dotnet test with Microsoft.Testing.Platform)\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*.Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration Release\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n      --\n      --report-trx\n      --coverage\n      --coverage-output-format cobertura\n```\n\n### 3. Publish results and coverage\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish TRX results'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish code coverage'\n  condition: always()\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/coverage.cobertura.xml'\n```\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Concern | VSTest@3 | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|---|\n| Runner | vstest.console | Test exe / `dotnet test` |\n| TRX reports | Built-in | `--report-trx` flag + NuGet extension |\n| Code coverage | `codeCoverageEnabled` | `--coverage` flag + NuGet extension |\n| Result format | `.trx` (same) | `.trx` (same) |\n| Coverage format | `.coverage` (binary) | Cobertura XML (natively) |\n\nThe `PublishTestResults@2` task works with both — TRX format is unchanged. The main win is Cobertura coverage output, which `PublishCodeCoverageResults@2` renders natively without conversion.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98833d07-44fc-48c5-85ae-d3e8441f030d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty - there's no repository to explore. The user is asking a general question about migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure DevOps pipelines. Let me provide guidance based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":796,"requestId":"4C20:16C73:D5201F:1093EB2:6A0129A1"},"id":"b1f0b5c1-7475-4463-b647-c41d1e2901ee","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:58:24.035Z","parentId":"803b9179-6dc9-4c7e-b37b-e78c4ffbc801"}
